body:
@MarcoFalke Just to reemphasize this point.  This is not only about resources.  Very powerful nodes can still be attacked if they have a mempool with some size limit.

I do agree that better wallet UI is needed, but that problem is not introduced by this pull.

If we don't make the default small enough to be safe, then most people will have to configure their own policy.  I suspect that will lead to a great many nodes limiting chains to much smaller counts.

@petertodd I've been following the CPFP and RBF discussions with interest. Not so much to entirely replace the tx chains we have, but to reduce the number of outputs necessary to pay network fees across the chain, and improve the all-or-none granularity of the tx set for inclusion in a block.

I gave a slightly more specific example of my use case on the bitcoin-dev list a few weeks ago: http://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010569.html   Basically, a brokered escrow transaction involving 3 parties where the seller and the buyer never communicate directly.

Yes, I am aware of and concerned about transaction maleability. I'm counting on BIP62 to significantly reduce that risk. I believe the txs we generate are already BIP62 compliant. We also compute a signature-free hash of every transaction as an alternate txid so that we can at least recognize our txs in the blockchain even if their scripts have been tweaked in transit. Any issued txs downstream from that altered tx would have to be redone, of course, which is a pain in the neck and extremely inconvenient to all involved.
